ce:section.ce:para:
The application of this sensing method for Fe2+ and Fe3+ ion detection was also examined to verify the utilization of CQDs as the turn-off probe for real water samples, which are tap water and Portage Lake water. To check the application for CQDs in the real water samples, different concentrations of Fe2+ and Fe3+ were added into the tap water and Portage Lake water (Table 3
                        ), while keeping the concentration of CQDs constant at 0.05 μg/mL. UV–vis absorption spectra and then PL spectra were collected (Fig. 6
                         and Fig. 7
                        ). The recoveries for detecting Fe2 + ions in real water samples ranged from 71.1 % to 103.7 % and for detecting Fe3 + ions, the recovery range was 84.4 % to 121.%. These results showing that this method has an acceptable accuracy compared to previous reported values [36]. One reason can the pre-treatment process (centrifugation and filtration) of real water samples before spiking Fe ions, while in this work, the real water samples were used without any pre-treatment. In addition, the difference in the recovery range of this work and previous studies [36] can be due to higher LOD in this work.
